er 26: Theater -- tPart IX. Mass Media -- tChapter 27: Film and Photography -- tChapter 28: Newspapers and Radio -- tPart X. Exchange -- tChapter 29: Americanism -- tChapter 30: Global Resonances -- tPart XI. Reaction -- tChapter 31: Anti-Semitism -- tChapter 32: Black Vienna -- tChapter 33: Brown Vienna -- tPart XII. Power -- tChapter 34: Campaigns and Elections -- tChapter 35: Communication and Propaganda -- tChapter 36: Political Violence -- tChronology -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Persons0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn encyclopedic selection of original documents from the Austrian capital's pathbreaking, progressive interwar period, translated and with contextualizing introductions and commentaries.Immediately after World War I, in 1919, the Austrian capital Vienna elected a Social Democratic majority that persisted until 1934. The city's leaders, together with its intellectuals, boldly imagined a new society that would be economically just, scientifically rigorous, and radically democratic. "Red Vienna" undertook experiments in public housing, welfare, and education while maintaining a world-class presence in science, music, literature, theater, andother fields of cultural production. Though Red Vienna eventually fell victim to fascist violence, it left a rich legacy with potential to inform our own tumultuous times. The Red Vienna Sourcebook provides scholars and students with a selection of some 280 key texts from the period, carefully translated and introduced. These texts connect readers to the era's most fascinating discussions, movements, and personalities and will be of interest to such diverse disciplines as architecture, economics, film studies, history, Jewish studies, literary studies, music, philosophy, political science, psychology, sociology, sports, and women's studies. Rob McFarland isProfessor of German Literature, Film and Culture at Brigham Young University. Georg Spitaler is a researcher at the Austrian Labor History Society. Ingo Zechner is Director of the Ludwig Boltzmann Institute for Digital History.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPopular culture-Austria-Vienna-History-20th century-Sources. 0aVienna (Austria)-History-20th century-Sources. 0aVienna (Austria)-Social policy-Sources. 4aGerman History. 4aJewish Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh  aAnti-Semitism.  aAustria.  aAustro-Hungarian Empire.  aEducation Reform.  aElections.  aFeminism.  aJudaism.  aMarxism.  aSocialism.  aVienna School.  aWeimar Republic.  aWomen's Movement.  aart history.  akineticism.  alabor movements.  anature.  apropaganda.  aradio.  aurban development.1 aBorn, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgoyne, Nicole G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuma, Veronika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFichna, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKopp, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKudryashova, Aleks, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFarland, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFarland, Rob, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNemec, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPilz, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwa